How to Integrate LLMSecurityGuard in an Organization?

Step 1 — Deploy It as a Secure Gateway

LLMSecurityGuard is deployed as a standalone API service (Flask app).

You can run it:

On a VM

In a Docker container

Inside Kubernetes

On-prem or in the cloud (AWS, Azure, GCP)

Once deployed, it becomes the mandatory entry point for all LLM requests.

Instead of:

Application → LLM

You now have:

Application → LLMSecurityGuard → LLM

Step 2 — Connect It to Your LLM Provider

Inside the gateway, configure the LLM adapter:

Cloud LLM (OpenAI, Anthropic, etc.)

Store API keys securely (env variables or secret manager)

On-prem LLM (e.g., local model or internal inference server)

Point to internal LLM endpoint

The organization does not need to modify their LLM — only redirect traffic through the gateway.

Step 3 — Integrate Authentication & RBAC

Replace the demo token system with:

OAuth / JWT

Corporate SSO

Active Directory integration

API key management system

Map users to roles:

Admin

Developer

Analyst

External user

This ensures only authorized users can submit prompts.

Step 4 — Configure Security Policies

Customize:

Risk score thresholds

Manual review triggers

Sensitive keyword lists

PII detection rules

Rate limits per user or service

Security teams define the rules based on organizational policy.

Step 5 — Connect Logging to SIEM

Export logs to:

Splunk

Datadog

ELK stack

SIEM tools

This enables:

Audit trails

Compliance reporting

Incident response

